Sponges ( McLay 1993: 139 , under
Dromidiopsis dubia
).

Mclaydromia

n. gen.
can be readily distinguished from 

Dromidiopsis

sensu nobis (
Fig. 6
) as follows: 1) abdominal segments free (abdominal segments 5 and 6 fused together in 

Dromidiopsis

); 2) propodus of P4 and P5 subequal in size (dissimilar, much longer on P5, in 

Dromidiopsis

); 3) when extended forward, P5 barely overreaching last lateral tooth of carapace (much long, reaching about outer orbital angle in 

Dromidiopsis

); 4) female sutures 7/8 wide apart, oblique, getting progressively close to each other as they run forward over thoracic sternites (getting much closed to each other at level of P3 and subparallel in 

Dromidiopsis

); 5) apertures of spermathecae at level of P2 and placed wide apart from each other, on tubercles (at level of P1 or just behind and lying close together, on central prominence, in 

Dromidiopsis

); and 6) male uropods showing as dorsal plates that are obliquely oriented (vertically oriented in 

Dromidiopsis

).
